In dedicating his work to Quaen Elisabeth, Sir Henry Savile passed this just eu- logy on Malmesbury: ‘Inter quos cum et nar- rationis fide, et judicii maturitate, principem lo- cum teneat Guilielmus Malmesburiensis, homo, ut erant illa tempora, literate doctus, qni septin- gentorum plus minus annorum res tanta fide et diligentia pertexuit ut e nostris prope solus his- torici munus explesse videatur.'¹

The manuscript from which Savile's edition was printed was either carelessly transcribed, or the volume was incorrectly printed: the text abounds with gross errors, which the table os errata printed at the end of the work very inade- quately remedies. From occasionel notices in the margin, it is evident that Savile consulted more than one manuscript: but instead of having followed any one in particular, he seems to have formed his text from several. The present Editor has not met with any manuscript which entirely agrees with Savile’s text: the Royal MS. in the British Museum, 13. Β. xlx. comes nearest to it, but does not thoroughly agree with it.
